<Layout title="Causes of Infertility">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Causes of Infertility</h1>
			<p>Understanding the factors that contribute to infertility, with statistics and research-backed data.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>Overview: Who is Affected?</h2>
		<p>Infertility affects approximately <strong>1 in 6 couples</strong> trying to conceive. Contrary to common perception, infertility is not primarily a female issue—causes are distributed relatively equally between partners.</p>

		<div class="card stats-card">
			<h3>Distribution of Infertility Causes</h3>
			<table>
				<thead>
					<tr>
						<th>Attribution</th>
						<th>Percentage</th>
					</tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Female factors only</td>
						<td>~35%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Male factors only</td>
						<td>~35%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Combined male and female factors</td>
						<td>~20%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Unexplained (no identifiable cause)</td>
						<td>~10-25%</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
			<p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://www.reproductivefacts.org/browse-resources/frequently-asked-questions/faq-about-infertility/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASRM ReproductiveFacts.org</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556033/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NCBI StatPearls</a></p>
		</div>

		<h2>Female Factor Infertility</h2>

		<h3>Ovulatory Disorders</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p>Problems with ovulation account for approximately <strong>25% of female infertility cases</strong>. The most common cause is polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS).</p>

			<h4>Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)</h4>
			<ul>
				<li>Affects <strong>5-20%</strong> of women of reproductive age worldwide</li>
				<li>Responsible for <strong>70-80%</strong> of anovulatory infertility cases</li>
				<li>Women with PCOS: <strong>40%</strong> experience infertility</li>
				<li><strong>90-95%</strong> of anovulatory women seeking fertility treatment have PCOS</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Sources: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459251/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NCBI StatPearls - PCOS</a>, <a href="https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/polycystic-ovary-syndrome" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WHO Fact Sheet</a>, <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3872139/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PMC - Epidemiology of PCOS</a></p>
		</div>

		<h3>Tubal Factor</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p>Blocked or damaged fallopian tubes account for <strong>20-35%</strong> of female infertility cases.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Caused by pelvic inflammatory disease, endometriosis, or prior surgery</li>
				<li>May result from sexually transmitted infections (chlamydia, gonorrhea)</li>
				<li>Prior ectopic pregnancy increases risk</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556033/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NCBI StatPearls - Female Infertility</a></p>
		</div>

		<h3>Endometriosis</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p>Endometriosis contributes to <strong>10-15%</strong> of female infertility cases.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Affects <strong>2-10%</strong> of women of childbearing age in general population</li>
				<li>Present in <strong>25-50%</strong> of infertile women</li>
				<li>Found in <strong>30-50%</strong> of women with endometriosis are infertile</li>
				<li>Infertile women are <strong>6-8 times more likely</strong> to have endometriosis than fertile women</li>
				<li>Reduces monthly fecundity rate to <strong>2-10%</strong> (vs. 15-20% in normal couples)</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Sources: <a href="https://www.asrm.org/practice-guidance/practice-committee-documents/endometriosis-and-infertility-a-committee-opinion-2012/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASRM Committee Opinion</a>, <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5715862/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PMC - Clinical Management of Endometriosis</a></p>
		</div>

		<h3>Uterine Factors</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p>Uterine abnormalities account for <strong>10-15%</strong> of female infertility cases.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Fibroids:</strong> Present in 20-40% of women; submucosal fibroids most impact fertility</li>
				<li><strong>Uterine septum:</strong> Most common congenital uterine anomaly; associated with recurrent loss</li>
				<li><strong>Asherman's syndrome:</strong> Intrauterine adhesions from prior surgery or infection</li>
				<li><strong>Polyps:</strong> May interfere with implantation</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556033/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NCBI StatPearls - Female Infertility</a></p>
		</div>

		<h3>Diminished Ovarian Reserve</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<p>Reduced quantity and quality of eggs, either due to age or other factors.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Fertility begins declining around age 32 and more rapidly after 37</li>
				<li>By age 40, chance of natural conception per cycle drops to ~5%</li>
				<li>Premature ovarian insufficiency affects ~1% of women under 40</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h2>Male Factor Infertility</h2>

		<div class="card">
			<p>Male factors are the sole cause in <strong>~20%</strong> of infertility cases and contribute to an additional <strong>30-40%</strong>.</p>

			<h4>Common Causes</h4>
			<table>
				<thead>
					<tr>
						<th>Cause</th>
						<th>Prevalence in Male Infertility</th>
					</tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Varicocele</td>
						<td>~40% of infertile men</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Idiopathic (unexplained)</td>
						<td>~25%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Obstruction</td>
						<td>~10-15%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Hormonal disorders</td>
						<td>~5-10%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Genetic factors</td>
						<td>~5-10%</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Testicular failure</td>
						<td>~10%</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>

			<h4>Sperm Abnormalities</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Low sperm count (oligospermia):</strong> &lt;15 million/mL</li>
				<li><strong>Poor motility (asthenospermia):</strong> &lt;40% motile</li>
				<li><strong>Abnormal morphology (teratospermia):</strong> &lt;4% normal forms</li>
				<li><strong>Azoospermia:</strong> No sperm in ejaculate (affects 1% of men, 10-15% of infertile men)</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Sources: <a href="https://resolve.org/learn/infertility-101/underlying-causes/male-factor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RESOLVE - Male Factor</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562258/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NCBI StatPearls - Male Infertility</a>, <a href="https://www.auanet.org/guidelines-and-quality/guidelines/male-infertility" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AUA/ASRM Guidelines</a></p>
		</div>

		<h2>Unexplained Infertility</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<p>In <strong>10-25%</strong> of couples, no cause is identified after standard testing.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>All standard tests (semen analysis, ovulation, tubal patency) are normal</li>
				<li>May reflect subtle issues not detected by current testing</li>
				<li>Treatment typically progresses from timed intercourse → IUI → IVF</li>
				<li>Prognosis is generally good; many conceive with treatment</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://www.reproductivefacts.org/browse-resources/frequently-asked-questions/faq-about-infertility/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASRM ReproductiveFacts.org</a></p>
		</div>

		<h2>Lifestyle and Environmental Factors</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h4>Smoking</h4>
			<ul>
				<li>Smokers are <strong>twice as likely</strong> to experience infertility</li>
				<li>Reduces IVF success rates by up to 50%</li>
				<li>Increases miscarriage risk</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://www.asrm.org/news-and-events/asrm-news/press-releasesbulletins/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASRM</a></p>

			<h4>Weight</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>12%</strong> of female infertility is attributed to weight issues (over or under)</li>
				<li>Obesity reduces IVF success rates</li>
				<li>BMI &gt;30 or &lt;18.5 associated with ovulatory dysfunction</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://www.fertilityanswers.com/13-stats-know-infertility/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fertility Answers</a></p>

			<h4>Age</h4>
			<ul>
				<li>Female fertility peaks in early-to-mid 20s</li>
				<li>Significant decline begins after age 35</li>
				<li>By 40, chance of conceiving per cycle is ~5%</li>
				<li>Male fertility also declines with age, though more gradually</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h2>Treatment Success by Cause</h2>
		<p>Understanding your diagnosis helps predict which treatments are most likely to succeed:</p>

		<table>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Diagnosis</th>
					<th>Best Initial Treatment</th>
					<th>Expected Success</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>PCOS / Anovulation</td>
					<td>Letrozole/Clomid</td>
					<td>~25-30% live birth with meds</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Unexplained</td>
					<td>IUI or IVF</td>
					<td>~40-50% cumulative with IUI; higher with IVF</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Mild male factor</td>
					<td>IUI</td>
					<td>~10-15% per cycle</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Severe male factor</td>
					<td>IVF with ICSI</td>
					<td>Similar to standard IVF</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Tubal factor</td>
					<td>IVF</td>
					<td>Age-dependent; 40-55% under 35</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Endometriosis</td>
					<td>Surgery ± IVF</td>
					<td>Variable; IVF comparable to tubal factor</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Diminished ovarian reserve</td>
					<td>IVF (± donor eggs)</td>
					<td>Lower with own eggs; 50-65% with donor</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

